article.headline: California 88, Oregon State 74
article.story: CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- Last time he visited Gill Coliseum, Amit Tamir had seven 3-pointers. For his most recent visit, he got six. "I like the baskets here," he said. "There's confidence in knowing that you did well before." Tamir finished with 20 points and 10 rebounds to lead California to a 88-74 victory over Oregon State Saturday night. The Golden Bears (9-9, 5-4 Pacific 10) have won three of their last four and extended their winning streak over the Beavers to 12 straight games. David Lucas had 25 points and nine rebounds for the Beavers (8-11, 2-7), losers of five straight. Cal went up 50-38 early in the second half on Tamir's 3-pointer. Another 3-pointer from the 6-foot-10 senior center made it 55-40. The Beavers could not get closer than nine points the rest of the way. "I know everyone looks mostly at his (Tamir's) shooting," Cal coach Ben Braun said. "But he's an all-around player and he showed that tonight." The Golden Bears took their biggest lead of the game when freshman Leon Powe's layup made it 70-56. Powe, who leads the Pac-10 in rebounding, finished with 20 points and 14 rebounds. It was his ninth double-double this season. "I think it's pretty obvious," Oregon State coach Jay John said. "Cal was just far too big, far to physical." Cal shot 53.6 percent overall for the game. The Bears jumped out to a 24-16 lead early, but freshman Angelo Tsagarakis hit a 3-pointer to narrow it to 24-19 for the Beavers. Tamir came back with his own 3 to extend the margin again. Oregon State got to within 27-26 on J.S. Nash's jumper. After Powe made one of a pair of free throws, Tsagarakis made a 3-pointer to briefly put the Beavers ahead 29-28. It was short-lived, as the Bears went on a 10-4 run to close out the first half with a 38-33 lead. "That's an explosive team," said Lamar Hurd, who had 10 points for the Beavers. "They can do that to anybody once they get going." The Beavers' 12-game losing streak to Cal is their longest to any conference opponent. The last time the Oregon State beat the Bears was back on March 5, 1998, a 46-43 win at the Oakland Arena. Tamir's seven 3-pointers in Cal's 84-71 win at Corvallis last season tied Gary Payton's Gill Coliseum record. In five career games against the Beavers, Tamir has hit on 19 of 29 3-point attempts.
